\pard\qc\b\fs30 CHAPTER 5\b0\fs24\par\par
\pard\qc\b IMPLEMENTATION OF CONCURRENCY CONTROL AND RECOVERY MECHANISMS\b0\par\par
\pard\b 5.1 Introduction to Transactions\b0\par
\pard\li360\b 5.1.1 Properties of Transactions\b0\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Atomicity: all operations inside a transaction are completed together, or none of them are applied.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Consistency: a transaction moves the database from one valid state to another valid state.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Isolation: one transaction does not interfere with another concurrent transaction.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Durability: once committed, the changes remain permanent even after failure or restart.\par
\pard\li360\b 5.1.2 States of a Transaction\b0\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Active: transaction is currently executing.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Partially committed: all statements are executed, but commit is not yet finalized.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Committed: transaction has completed successfully and changes are permanent.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Failed: transaction could not complete because of an error or interruption.\par
\pard\li720\fi-360 \bullet\tab Aborted: all changes are rolled back and the database returns to the earlier consistent state.\par
\pard\b 5.2 Transaction Control Language (TCL)\b0\par
\pard\li360\b 5.2.1 SAVEPOINT\b0\par
\pard SAVEPOINT is used to create an intermediate point inside a transaction. The database can roll back to that point without cancelling the entire transaction.\par
\pard\li360\b 5.2.2 COMMIT\b0\par
\pard COMMIT permanently saves all changes performed by the current transaction.\par
\pard\li360\b 5.2.3 ROLLBACK\b0\par
\pard ROLLBACK cancels uncommitted changes. It can also be used with SAVEPOINT to partially undo work.\par
